00:19:23.576 --> 00:19:27.086
My name is Julia Lowe. I'm a first-year PhD student in computational

333
00:19:27.156 --> 00:19:30.796
biology and bioinformatics at Duke University, and today I'm going to be speaking

334
00:19:30.856 --> 00:19:34.326
about my project, developing a model for glioblastoma recurrence

335
00:19:34.416 --> 00:19:37.626
prediction that involves a multi-omic approach but is centered around

336
00:19:37.736 --> 00:19:38.556
histopathology.

337
00:19:41.936 --> 00:19:44.156
So a quick background for the cancer type we're studying.

338
00:19:44.316 --> 00:19:47.876
Glioblastoma is an extremely aggressive brain cancer with a median

339
00:19:47.936 --> 00:19:51.256
survival of less than two years. One of the biggest clinical

340
00:19:51.336 --> 00:19:54.696
challenges is that recurrence timing varies widely from patient to

341
00:19:54.716 --> 00:19:58.616
patient. Traditionally, when patients are diagnosed with glioblastoma, they receive

342
00:19:58.756 --> 00:20:02.546
a surgical resection, be treated with chemo and radiation, but it almost

343
00:20:02.636 --> 00:20:06.456
universally comes back. So the main key question we're trying to answer

344
00:20:06.536 --> 00:20:10.456
is, can we not only predict recurrence, but understand why some patients live

345
00:20:10.496 --> 00:20:14.076
much longer than others? And we use multiple modalities because each provides

346
00:20:14.116 --> 00:20:17.226
complementary information to help decode this question.

347
00:20:17.236 --> 00:20:20.786
The first modality that we're working with is H&amp;E slides, which can convey general

348
00:20:20.816 --> 00:20:24.716
information about tissue architecture, cellular density, and structure,

349
00:20:24.756 --> 00:20:27.676
as well as any sort of histologic heterogeneity patterns.

350
00:20:27.746 --> 00:20:31.526
And this is a very inexpensive, routinely collected modality, and thus is highly

351
00:20:31.536 --> 00:20:35.416
scalable. The other modality on the far right here are MRI images, which

352
00:20:35.436 --> 00:20:37.116
provide a whole tumor view of the tumor,

353
00:20:38.096 --> 00:20:41.876
conveying information about overall structure, size, any edema, as well as

354
00:20:41.916 --> 00:20:45.516
uncover imaging biomarkers, and this is also routinely collected in the clinical

355
00:20:45.596 --> 00:20:49.276
setting. In the middle here, we're leveraging two different types of spatial omics

356
00:20:49.316 --> 00:20:53.296
data. The first being Xenium, which is single-cell resolution in situ

357
00:20:53.596 --> 00:20:57.096
gene expression, as well as Codex, which is single-cell protein

358
00:20:57.116 --> 00:21:00.485
expression. And this can provide very rich data about cell identity,

359
00:21:00.876 --> 00:21:03.936
different transcript and proteome programs, as well as functional activity.

