00:21:07.825 --> 00:21:11.736
They're quite expensive, and the access to them is not universal across all

362
00:21:11.776 --> 00:21:15.596
labs here. So thus, the goal of my project is to incorporate information

363
00:21:15.676 --> 00:21:19.646
from all of these modalities, but focus my algorithm on the types of data that

364
00:21:19.696 --> 00:21:22.265
is routinely collectible in the clinical and research setting.

365
00:21:23.276 --> 00:21:25.816
So, a quick overview of the architecture of the proposed model.

366
00:21:26.186 --> 00:21:29.776
The main goal is to develop this prediction model that's centered on the routinely

367
00:21:29.956 --> 00:21:33.736
collected and available data, like the histology and the MRI images, while

368
00:21:33.816 --> 00:21:37.076
utilizing the richness that spatial data can provide as more as an

369
00:21:37.116 --> 00:21:40.876
explainability metric, as opposed to a direct input to the model

370
00:21:40.916 --> 00:21:44.836
itself. So we'll start with these H&amp;E whole slide images, incorporate relevant

371
00:21:44.896 --> 00:21:48.756
clinical metadata, as well as features derived from MRI scans, which we'll

372
00:21:48.836 --> 00:21:51.156
treat as patient-level covariates in the model.

373
00:21:51.756 --> 00:21:55.716
And for each of the H&amp;E whole slide images, we perform tile extraction to

374
00:21:55.736 --> 00:21:59.696
generate non-overlapping tiles from the whole slide image, and we feed it into

375
00:21:59.756 --> 00:22:03.556
a pathology foundation model, specifically Uni2 model, which we'll

376
00:22:03.596 --> 00:22:07.076
later fine-tune specifically for the task of recurrence prediction.

377
00:22:07.086 --> 00:22:10.676
And where the spatial data comes into play here, the Xenium and the Codex data,

378
00:22:10.716 --> 00:22:13.866
again, not as an input to the model, but rather for explainability.

379
00:22:13.876 --> 00:22:17.656
We can align this to the histology data that we have to get a better and more

380
00:22:17.696 --> 00:22:21.116
comprehensive picture of what's going on on a transcript and proteome level.

381
00:22:22.056 --> 00:22:25.376
So once we have the alignment of the spatial modalities, we can fine-tune the

382
00:22:25.416 --> 00:22:29.336
foundation model by adding an attention head specifically for the task of

383
00:22:29.376 --> 00:22:33.336
recurrence prediction, where we can identify tiles within the H&amp;E whole

384
00:22:33.376 --> 00:22:35.976
slide images that are implicated in recurrence timing.

385
00:22:36.455 --> 00:22:40.376
And the output to the model not only would we have a fully functional pipeline to

386
00:22:40.456 --> 00:22:44.056
develop a time-based to a recurrence, but also

387
00:22:44.096 --> 00:22:47.636
developing a more biological understanding of how recurrence

388
00:22:47.676 --> 00:22:50.996
manifest, and the mechanisms that drive recurrence, and why they're different from

389
00:22:51.016 --> 00:22:51.836
patient to patient.

390
00:22:53.526 --> 00:22:56.136
A quick overview to the cohort. We're starting with a very small

391
00:22:57.396 --> 00:23:01.296
sort of preliminary data set to set up the overall structure of the algorithm.

392
00:23:01.416 --> 00:23:05.326
So right now, I have 19 patients that are newly diagnosed GBM patients, all

393
00:23:05.376 --> 00:23:09.016
of whom received a total resection in their first primary surgery.

394
00:23:09.476 --> 00:23:12.716
Fifteen of these patients received standard chemo and radiation

395
00:23:12.776 --> 00:23:16.646
therapy, and four of these received, again, standard chemo and radiation,

396
00:23:16.776 --> 00:23:18.856
but in addition, a PD-1 inhibitor.

397
00:23:18.866 --> 00:23:22.326
And we have quite a variety in recurrence timing across each of these patients, as

398
00:23:22.356 --> 00:23:24.856
well as from different areas within the brain.

399
00:23:25.416 --> 00:23:29.196
And so I grouped the initial 19 sample cohort into three different groups based on

400
00:23:29.216 --> 00:23:33.196
recurrence timing, the short recurrence group, the intermediate group, and the long

401
00:23:33.256 --> 00:23:36.726
recurrence group. So right now, we're currently expanding this cohort, but this

