407
00:23:55.186 --> 00:23:58.666
And what we've seen from this preliminary analysis is that samples that

408
00:23:58.776 --> 00:24:02.186
have quite poor clinical outcomes, they have very short time to recurrences,

409
00:24:02.576 --> 00:24:05.226
display increased architectural disruption.

410
00:24:05.576 --> 00:24:08.836
While on the other end of the spectrum, samples that retain a much longer time to

411
00:24:08.856 --> 00:24:12.796
recurrences, we see clear segmentation and normal tissue

412
00:24:12.836 --> 00:24:14.476
architecture is more so retained.

413
00:24:14.856 --> 00:24:18.736
So we see quite clear areas of vasculature in other regions all the way on the

414
00:24:18.776 --> 00:24:22.096
right here, while on the left we see quite a large disruption in tissue

415
00:24:22.136 --> 00:24:25.984
architecture.The algorithm that I'm using to generate my tiles

416
00:24:26.084 --> 00:24:29.764
is called SlideFlow, and the reason we want to do this is because H&amp;E images are

417
00:24:29.824 --> 00:24:33.784
quite large and contain millions and millions of pixels, and by dividing them into

418
00:24:33.794 --> 00:24:37.264
these non-overlapping tiles, we can introduce them to a machine learning

419
00:24:37.344 --> 00:24:39.404
framework that the model can handle.

420
00:24:40.124 --> 00:24:43.924
So how this works is by overlaying a grid on top of the H&amp;E images, and we'll

421
00:24:43.944 --> 00:24:47.874
filter out any sort of background or out-of-focus or artifact regions, and

422
00:24:47.984 --> 00:24:51.834
each tile represents a particular piece from the H&amp;E whole slide

423
00:24:51.924 --> 00:24:52.204
image.

424
00:24:53.604 --> 00:24:56.804
Once we have each of these tiles, we can leverage the richness that foundation

425
00:24:56.844 --> 00:25:00.014
models can provide. So here I'm using the UniHeal foundation model.

426
00:25:00.984 --> 00:25:04.484
For my 19 samples, I generated the tiles for each of those, and then each tile is

427
00:25:04.524 --> 00:25:07.584
fed into the Uni encoder to generate embeddings.

428
00:25:07.784 --> 00:25:11.644
And then once we have the embeddings from all of the tiles, I've processed them and

429
00:25:11.824 --> 00:25:12.724
constructed a

430
00:25:13.924 --> 00:25:17.244
clustering graph here. So in the UMAP here, all of the tiles are

