00:25:21.024 --> 00:25:24.874
And what I've done is assigned the cluster identity for each of the tiles,

433
00:25:24.944 --> 00:25:28.884
mapping back to the H&amp;E whole slide images to see if they represent any sort of

434
00:25:28.923 --> 00:25:32.044
biological pattern and can be conserved across the cohort.

435
00:25:32.704 --> 00:25:35.964
For example, you can see cluster zero, which is the top one in the key here.

436
00:25:36.084 --> 00:25:39.624
This dark blue corresponds to regions annotated by the pathologist

437
00:25:39.724 --> 00:25:40.094
as

438
00:25:41.184 --> 00:25:44.424
necrotic areas. So we see that the foundation model can sort of capture

439
00:25:44.444 --> 00:25:45.944
biologically meaningful trends.

440
00:25:48.024 --> 00:25:49.144
And how we're going to fine-tune the

441
00:25:50.604 --> 00:25:54.364
pathology foundation model specifically for our task of recurrence prediction, we

442
00:25:54.424 --> 00:25:58.204
start with having the H&amp;E whole slide images that we use to attract pixels

443
00:25:58.284 --> 00:26:01.484
with, feed them into a foundation model, specifically UniHeal.

444
00:26:02.114 --> 00:26:05.764
And the early layers of the model will capture more general, broad

445
00:26:05.804 --> 00:26:09.734
histologic patterns, so things like cellular density, broad morphological

446
00:26:09.844 --> 00:26:12.644
patterns, and we'll freeze these early layers to

