00:26:43.004 --> 00:26:46.644
predictions. We can also use the gradient-weighted class activation

456
00:26:46.684 --> 00:26:50.494
mapping to identify which regions were most important in driving model predictions,

457
00:26:50.984 --> 00:26:54.964
as well as in attention map visualizations to see which tiles are most implicated

458
00:26:55.024 --> 00:26:56.924
in terms of recurrence differences.

459
00:26:57.334 --> 00:27:01.044
So this is how we'll visualize which areas corresponding to the H&amp;E whole slide

460
00:27:01.124 --> 00:27:03.924
images are most important in terms of recurrence differences.

461
00:27:05.444 --> 00:27:09.244
Now I'll get a brief introduction into the MRI approach that we're using.

462
00:27:09.764 --> 00:27:13.544
So for the MRI images, the first step involves pre-processing these, aligning the

463
00:27:13.564 --> 00:27:17.344
different sequences, removing any non-brain tissue, segmenting the tumor

464
00:27:17.364 --> 00:27:20.564
within the MRI to three different regions, whether it's the non-enhancing tumor

465
00:27:20.644 --> 00:27:23.704
core, the enhancing tumor, or outer edema and infiltration.

466
00:27:24.164 --> 00:27:27.864
We then calculate pixel value features and use a pyRadiomics pipeline to

467
00:27:27.904 --> 00:27:31.744
extract radiomic features and then perform feature reduction, as there could be

468
00:27:31.804 --> 00:27:35.784
quite a lot of features. And the main goal here is to identify features

469
00:27:35.804 --> 00:27:38.544
that aren't traditionally used in imaging biomarkers.

470
00:27:38.904 --> 00:27:42.724
So obviously, a patient that has quite a larger tumor is expected to have a

471
00:27:42.764 --> 00:27:45.764
worse clinical outcome, and we're trying to uncover more niche and

472
00:27:45.834 --> 00:27:47.144
non-traditionally used features.

473
00:27:49.264 --> 00:27:52.924
So here we're currently in the process of extracting radiomic

474
00:27:52.984 --> 00:27:53.984
features for our cohort,

